result.execSummary:
The defendant Vincent Tyrone Cannon was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. On one or more other charges, Vincent Tyrone Cannon was found not guilty. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Vincent Tyrone Cannon is presumed innocent of the not guilty charges.

  • Vincent Tyrone Cannon was found guilty of Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defense indicates the witness has been located and is available to testify this morning and she has spoken to this witess regarding the Court's previous admonishment. 
Defense calls RN - DSAT. Direct by defense. Cross by the State. Defense has no further witnesses. BTC: The defendant freely, knowingly, and voluntarily waives his right to testify and chooses to remain silent. The Defense rests. The State has no rebuttal witnesses. Defense motions for directed verdict. BTC: The court denies the motion for directed verdict.
The State withdraws its request for mistrial. Parties review JI outside the presence of the jury. Jury re-enters; Mr. Repischak gives closing arguments. The Defense gives closing arguments. Rebuttal by the State. Names are tumbled; alternate chosen. Oath #4 given.

Defendant Vincent Tyrone Cannon in court with attorney Michelle Marie Anderson.  Robert Scott Repischak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court Reporter: Leslie Johnson.
BTC: Victim's probation status is not to be elicited on direct or cross. The State is to notify his witness of the Courts ruling.
The jury enters the Courtroom at 9:10 am. Oath #2 given. The Court gives instructions to the jury. Mr. Repischak rives opening statements. State raises 904.04 due to defense mentioning the victim claimed he previously cut someone. BTC: The State prohibits defense from using the statement as raised in the 904.04 motion. The State also objects to defense indicating what the police officer allegedly said to the defendant. BTC: Parties are prohibited from referring to the statement allegedly made by the police officer on direct or cross. State calls JC - DSAT. Direct by the State. Cross xam by defense. Defense marks Ex #1-Victim pt consent form; Ex #2-Document signed by deft; Ex #3-photo of houses.  Ex #3 is moved into evidence/received & published. Redirect by State. State calls BM - DSAT. Direct by the State. Cross by defense. State calls GS - DSAT. Direct by the State. Cross by defense. State calls Officer Jon Principe - DSAT. Direct by the State. State marks Ex #4, moves into evidence/received. Ex #1 & 2 are included in Ex 4, therefore are moved into evidence/received. Cross xam by defense. The Defense asks for directed verdict as they believe the State has not met their burden. BTC: The Court denies the motion. Defense marks a portion of Ex #1 as Ex #1a. The Court approves and the exhibit is moved into evidence and received. The State has no further testimony and rests. Defense calls SW - DSAT. Direct by the Defense. The witness has uttered the issues discussed when the Court ordered not allowed under 904.04. The State moves for mistrial.  Defense does not intend to argue self defense and understands the statement cannot be taken back but does not agree that a mistrial is appropriate. BTC: The Court reserves ruling regarding mistrial. The Court wil give a curative instruction at this juncture that the last statement should be disregarded and should not be considered in the jury's deliberations. The witness is admonished about the statement and any future utterances. Defense continues direct exam. Cross xam by the State. The State again moves for mistrial due to the witness indicating there were 'threats'. Defense indicates that the State's questions continue to go back to the incident. BTC: Ruling is reserved on the matter of mistrial. Redirect by Defense. The Defense's final witness has not returned. The Court is in recess. Parties review jury instructions outside the presence of the jury. Defense has had her investigator attempt to reach the witness she is waiting for. Both the State and the Defense have served this witness. The phone number they have is invalid. Defense is asking that the trial be adjourned to tomorrow morning. The State does not object. The defense does not request a warrant at this time. If the witness does not appear tomorrow, the witness will not be allowed to be used.  The Court has marked copies of the subpoena's from both the State and the Defense for the witness as Court's exhibit #1 & 2. Final instrutions are reviewed.

BTC: Matter will be adjourned for the day.

Defendant Vincent Tyrone Cannon in court with attorney Michelle Marie Anderson.  Robert Scott Repischak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court Reporter: Patricia Schaefer.
The State places the final offer on the record. The defendant rejects the offer and wishes to go to trial. Jury enters; Oath #! administered. Voir dire by Ms. Anderson. Parties exercise peremptory challenges. Jury is chosen. Parties agree on the panel as chosen. The Court gives preliminary instructions to the panel.
